{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a4531058-6e7b-4630-a24b-9347ade3ad60","content":"The template has a solid foundation but has a few issues before it's NuGet-ready:\n\n**🔴 Functional bug:**\n- The `Framework` symbol is missing a `\"replaces\"` property (e.g., `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"`). Without it, the user's framework choice won't actually be substituted into the project files — the template will always output `net9.0`.\n\n**🟡 Recommended additions:**\n- **`$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation and editor intellisense.\n- **`groupIdentity`** — Useful if you plan to publish multiple related templates (e.g., `\"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n- **`preferNameDirectory`** — Typically `true` for project templates so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory.\n\n**🟡 Missing content:**\n- The directory is empty aside from `.template.config/` — there are no actual source files to scaffold. You'll need at least a `.csproj` and a `Program.cs` (or similar) for the template to produce anything.\n\n**✅ Looks good:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `sourceName`, `author`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all properly defined.\n\nIn short: **not ready yet** — fix the `replaces` gap on the Framework symbol and add actual project source files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3d4a8ac5-452b-4292-97f3-c94e75465f43","outputTokens":349},"id":"f72a58c4-e2ca-4b0c-ae32-97bc8628fbe8","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:39:19.683Z","parentId":"ed98edb9-aa09-446f-a4dd-36144c340476"}
